<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities issued an arrest warrant for the tanker captain suspected of drinking before his ship ran aground, causing a 1,000-square-mile oil slick that expanded Saturday under shifting wind and currents. A prosecutor said the captain admitted drinking on board the tanker before it went aground, according to court papers obtained by The Oregonian of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> newspaper. One of the first investigators to board the Exxon Valdez asked <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> what the problem was, and the captain replied, `` I think you're looking at it,'' the newspaper reported in its Sunday editions. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s governor threatened to close the Trans-Alaska Pipeline if the oil industry fails to protect against future spills. The bulk of the 10.1-million-gallon slick began moving toward <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON> about 50 miles southeast of here, threatening the home waters of fishermen who have struggled to save endangered fish hatcheries. About 800 miles of beach have been tainted so far in the biggest oil spill in the nation's history, officials said. Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said the state will require `` absolute proof that equipment is in place'' to combat future oil spills. `` If it's not done, we're authorized to close the pipeline,'' he said Some 85 percent of the state's $ 2 billion budget comes from the pipeline, and although the state has a $ 10 billion savings account, oil production on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s North slope accounts for 25 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Baily </PERSON> said Saturday that criminal charges were filed late Friday against <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, 42, captain of the tanker that crashed into <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION> on March 24. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> fired <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> on Thursday, the same day the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> revealed blood and urine tests taken about nine hours after the accident showed he had been under the influence of alcohol. Charges filed in <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> accuse <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> of operating a motorcraft while under the influence of alcohol, reckless endangerment and the negligent discharge of oil, all misdemeanors. The three offenses carry combined maximum sentences of two years and three months in prison, and fines totaling up to $ 10,000. District Attorney <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Weeks </PERSON> said if convicted, <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> would have to spend at least 30 days in jail because he has two prior drunken driving convictions in the past five years. Valdez Magistrate <PERSON> Tracee </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnell </PERSON> signed the arrest warrant for <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, and set bond at $ 50,000. Authorities believe he left the state several days ago, but <PERSON> Baily </PERSON> said the state would seek his extradition. Police in <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>'s hometown of <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, said Saturday they did not know his whereabouts. The Oregonian said two crewmen told authorities they saw <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> drinking in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> before the ship left port. A statement filed by <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Linton </PERSON>, an assistant district attorney in <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>, said one crewman saw <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> consume four alcoholic drinks while still in port. <PERSON> Linton </PERSON>'s affidavit said two other unidentified witnesses said they smelled alcohol on <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>'s breath when the captain was on the bridge, the newspaper reported. `` One witness said that <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> appeared to be under the influence of intoxicating beverages and that his balance was not good,'' <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> said in the affidavit. However, all crewmen interviewed by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> state troopers have said <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> `` did not appear to be intoxicated,'' <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> apparently told investigators he drank one beer before leaving port and a couple of bottles of `` moussy,'' a beverage containing 0.5 percent alcohol, after he returned to the ship, <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> say they're investigating possible felony violations of the Clean Water Act, which prohibits the `` negligent discharge of a pollutant into navigable waters.'' Exxon is liable for millions of dollars in fines under state law if it is proven to be negligent in causing the spill and cleaning it up. Shifting wind drove the main body of the slick east toward <LOCATION> Hinchenbrook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, which forms the primary boundary between the sound and the Gulf of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. The movement of the oil toward the rich fishing grounds at the mouth of the <LOCATION> Copper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> stirred fear in <LOCATION> Cordova </LOCATION>, which lies on the east side of the sound. Some <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON> fishermen, who had mounted a bold effort to protect the hatcheries on the west side, headed back toward their home port to battle the oil there. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietrick </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> praised the <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON> fishermen as the `` backbone'' of the cleanup and containment effort so far. Leaders in the fishing and tourist town of <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION>, the first community downstream from Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> to the west, also went on the offensive, deploying 10,000 feet of boom the town ordered from a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> manufacturer to protect salmon river habitats. `` We're not going to let it happen,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gieseler </PERSON>, mayor of the town 125 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION>. `` We're taking our own initiative.'' At the Kenai Fjords National Park, near <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION>, a team was sent out to survey wildlife and evaluate the state of the park before oil reaches the rocky shores, spokeswoman Dixie Dies said. The park will count on the city of <LOCATION> Seward </LOCATION> for boom and other protective measures, she said. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> rejected a plea from oil producers to ease restrictions placed on tanker traffic into <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> following the spill. The <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Richfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said tanker movement from the marine terminal of the trans-Alaska oil pipeline needs to be stepped up to ensure adequate supplies on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. On Friday, wholesale gasoline prices surged as commodities traders speculated that the squeeze in oil supplies caused by the disastrous spill wo n't ease soon. Gas prices at the pump jumped by as much as 10 cents a gallon in parts of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Normally three to four loaded tankers leave <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> daily. Since the spill, only five have made it out. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has ordered tugboat escorts until the tankers pass the grounded <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON>. Local harbor pilots are required to accompany the tankers for longer distances than usual. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said the restrictions would not be lifted until the <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> is refloated and moved to a safe anchorage, possibly next week. Workers continued Saturday to pump oil from the crippled tanker onto the Exxon <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Biologists walking beaches have counted 520 oiled birds representing 20 species, fish and game officials said. Ten sea otters and 27 oiled birds were taken to <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> for cleaning, and federal bird experts said more than 1,000 tainted birds _ some alive, some dead _ had been spotted on a single island. They expected the number to increase dramatically. Wildlife experts also were considering the possibility of sending some sea otters to other states for care and rehabilitation. Biologists say they expect to be inundated by otters, the marine mammal most vulnerable to oil contamination because of the loss of insulation and buoyancy of their fur. A sablefish harvest set to open today was canceled because of the spill. Officials previously halted the shrimp harvest, which was open for about two weeks before the spill and was to have run until mid-April. Meanwhile, another in a series of class-action lawsuits was filed Friday. A class-action complaint by <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Belli </PERSON>, on behalf of area fishermen, asked for $ 2 billion, half of it in punitive damages.
