<HEAD>South Africa Threatens To Remove U.N. Force After Guerrilla Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with revised casualty toll in
fighting; U.N. team sent to investigate; pickup graf 15 pvs `Fewer than...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> reported major clashes with guerrillas hours before <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> began its transition to independence Saturday and said it may ask the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> force monitoring the process to leave. Government-run radio said early Sunday that 36 guerrillas were killed and two captured in fighting Friday night with <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> police, who suffered two deaths and nine injuries. The figures, attributed to a spokesman for territorial Administrator-General <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, slightly revised those given Saturday by South African officials. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said Saturday that 38 guerrillas and two territorial policemen were killed when guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>, infiltrated from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> on Friday evening. `` This is a most serious development,'' said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>. The reported attack came hours before a formal cease-fire took effect and a 20-nation <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force began overseeing the end of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 74-year rule over <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. Police blocked thousands of <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> supporters who tried to march in the capital to celebrate the transition. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> accused the rebels of a flagrant violation of a pledge to halt hostilities and said he had complained to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>. Unless there is a satisfactory response from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would feel compelled to ask the peacekeeping force to leave `` until <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> can be brought to its senses.'' In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nadia </PERSON> <PERSON> Younes </PERSON> released a statement from <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> saying: `` The secretary-general is greatly concerned that such incidents have been reported. He has told Mr. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> that UNTAG -LRB- the U.N. Transition Assistance Group -RRB- is immediately sending a team to investigate the reports.'' <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Special Representative <PERSON> Martti </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON> sent four senior <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military, civilian, and police personnel to northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to investigate the South African report. He was expected to make his report by Sunday evening. An official of <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>, which has waged a war for independence since 1966, said the organization would need a day or so to determine what had happened but added that <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> `` has gone out of its way to avoid conflict.'' According to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> indicated he might agree that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> could reactivate its troops to guard against <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> operations. But the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman said the secretary-geeneral would have no comment on <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s remarks. Later at a news conference, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> troops will be allowed to leave their bases to search for the guerrillas involved in the fighting if police ca n't control the situation. South African and <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> forces were confined to their bases as of Saturday under the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan but <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> units had not complied. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> interrupted his airport news conference to take a call from <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>. He then said that <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON> and Gen. <PERSON> Prem </PERSON> <PERSON> Chand </PERSON>, the UNTAG commander, said certain South African units would be released from their bases to provide support to the police and the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> group would monitor the South African movement. Fewer than 800 of the 4,500 military personnel assigned to the UNTAG have arrived in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. There had been no fighting since September between South African and <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> forces, which were supposed to be restricted to their bases as of midnight Friday under U.N. Resolution 435. The resolution establishes a process for elections in November leading to independence early next year for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s last territory. British Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, completing an African tour, flew into <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> to meet with <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials and British members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> monitoring force. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said a special session of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> should be called to consider the alleged SWAPO incursion. `` This a most serious challenge to the authority of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the agreement, and we condemn it totally,'' she said. There was a tense 30-minute standoff outside the capital when about 100 policemen confronted up to 20,000 <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> supporters marching to <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> from the black township of <LOCATION> Katatura </LOCATION>, seeking to celebrate the start of the independence process. Church leaders persuaded the marchers to return to <LOCATION> Katatura </LOCATION>, where celebration rallies by rival political factions were held during the day. About 400 <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> supporters reached downtown <LOCATION> Windhoek </LOCATION> and held a rally across from a luxury hotel. About 30 policemen watched but did not interfere as the crowd chanted, `` SWAPO, we win!'' Until independence, administration of the territory and responsibility for law enforcement will remain in the hands of <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, appointed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> since it captured the territory from the Germans in World War I. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers will monitor the election in November of a constituent assembly. The assembly will later set up a black majority government. Of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s 1.3 million residents, about 70,000 are white. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is favored in the pre-independence elections, but whether it can gain the two-thirds support needed to have complete control over the drafting of a constitution is uncertain. The <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> agreed to a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> independence plan for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> in December as part of a southwestern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> accord that also calls for <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troops to be withdrawn from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>.
