<TEXT>
 Hollywood song-and-dance man <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> was released from the hospital Sunday after a bout with pneumonia. `` He's at home now, resting,'' said <PERSON> Beebe </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>, a publicist for <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, 76, had been admitted to <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> hospital Wednesday under a pseudonym. `` He came in quietly,'' said hospital spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>. `` His physicians did n't want him to be bothered by phone calls or visitors.'' The illness forced the entertainer to cancel a weekend performance of his one-man show, `` Evening with <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>'' at the <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Theater spokeswoman <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamlin </PERSON> said the performance was not rescheduled and refunds would be given to 1,300 fans. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> starred in such films as `` An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>'' and `` Anchors Aweigh,'' with <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON>. He is probably best known for his splash dance in `` Singin' in the Rain,'' which he also co-directed.
