<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Divers pulled seven bodies from a murky, rain-swollen river Sunday where at least that many people died when a 50-year-old <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> highway bridge collapsed. The search for more victims continued but was hampered by bridge debris and muddy waters, said state <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Durham </PERSON>. The cause of the collapse was unknown. Searchers did not know how many victims might be in the river, said <PERSON> Leroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bledsoe </PERSON>, team director for nine divers working at the site. Authorities said they had found a tractor-trailer rig and four cars which plunged into the river when a large chunk of the two-lane roadway fell 25 feet into the river about 8:45 p.m. CST Saturday. They planned to continue to search `` until we're sure there are no other vehicles or victims in there,'' <PERSON> Bledsoe </PERSON> said. The collapse left a 60-foot gap in the two-lane, northbound bridge carrying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Highway 51 over the <LOCATION> Hatchie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> five miles north of here and about 45 miles north of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>. A companion, two-lane bridge for southbound traffic was unaffected. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said bridge-building experts planned to study the bridge to try to find out why it collapsed. `` We've got the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> here. Their bridge survey team is going to survey the pilings of both bridges and do some soundings and we'll just have to go from there,'' he said. State bridge inspectors plan to meet Monday morning with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZAT