<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Evie </PERSON>, an 8-year-old female giraffe, died Sunday about 11 hours after falling on her side, zoo officials said. `` She passed away at 2:30 a.m.,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Grannon </PERSON>, operations curator for the Mesker Park Zoo. The body was taken to <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> for an autopsy to determine the cause of death, he said. Zoo director <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said <PERSON> Evie </PERSON> fell flat on her side Saturday about 3:15 p.m., but he was not sure what caused the accident. `` She was kind of running around in the sun when all four feet went our from under her and she landed on her side,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. `` We do n't know if the wind was knocked out of her or whether she hit her head.'' <PERSON> Evie </PERSON> had been on her back since the accident, and attempted about every 30 minutes to get back on her feet, zoo officials said. Zoo veterinarians Dr. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Epperson </PERSON> treated <PERSON> Evie </PERSON> Saturday night with relaxants, pain relievers and fluids, and even took X-rays of her neck and her legs but found nothing broken, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Evie </PERSON>, worth $ 12,000 to $ 20,000, came to the zoo in 1982 from <LOCATION> Abilene </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Her mate, <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON>, came from the <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zoo </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, in 1981, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said.
