<HEAD>Third World Debt Relief Plan Gets Major Boost from Industrialized
Nations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``The $1.3 trillion...'' to make riots
in February sted last month; picks up 12th graf pvs, bgng: ``The endorsement...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's new plan to provide debt relief for Third World countries received a major boost on Sunday when it won endorsement from the world's leading industrialized countries. The endorsement was contained in a joint communique adopted by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. It was issued following almost eight hours of closed-door discussions conducted by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and his foreign counterparts. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal was not mentioned by name in the three-page joint statement, but the discussion of the changes needed in current policy showed that the finance ministers were in general support of the proposals outlined by <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> in a March 10 speech. `` Debt strategy should be strengthened by placing greater emphasis on voluntary debt relief and debt service reduction in agreement with the commercial banks as a complement to new lending,'' the finance ministers said. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said that he was pleased with the endorsement contained in the joint statement, saying it was unusually detailed on what approaches now need to be taken and very specific on the need for prompt action by the international lending agencies. `` There was broad support for strengthening the debt strategy along the lines of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposals,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told reporters after the meeting had ended. Canadian Finance Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> called the new debt strategy an important step forward in solving the seven-year-long debt crisis. `` We have a good agreement and we have good support demonstrated for the proposal,'' he told reporters. A senior <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> official, who briefed reporters, said that while the communique did not mention specific support to be provided by other countries, he expected such announcements would be made later in the week. The administration is looking for countries running large trade surpluses, such as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, to offer to support the debt reduction effort by providing money for new loans. The <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan represents a major departure from the debt approach pursued by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, which had repeatedly rejected proposals for broad-based debt forgiveness. The $ 1.3 trillion burden of Third World debt has crippled the economies of developing nations and sparked economic and political unrest in many emerging democracies in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Riots left at least 270 people dead in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> in February after the government announced a new austerity program to please that country's creditors The endorsement by <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s major allies was the first step in a sales strategy the administration has put together. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> now takes the proposal before meetings on Monday and Tuesday of the steering committees of the 151-nation <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. The two major lending organizations have key roles to play in implementation of the new debt relief approach, which the administration hopes will shave the current debt burden by 20 percent. In other comments, the seven industrialized countries reaffirmed their commitment to stabilize the dollar, saying either a sharp increase or decline in the greenback's value would be seen as harmful to worldwide economic growth and would trigger joint intervention by the nations to buy or sell dollars. The countries also told the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that it needs to do more to reduce its huge budget deficits and said countries, such as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which were running large trade surpluses should continue to promote domestic demand in order to provide markets for foreign goods. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies have been complaining that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s expected $ 170 billion federal budget deficit this year threatens worldwide growth by driving up interest rates, a situation which also adds to the debt payment burden of poor nations. The discussions took place at <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION>, an estate on the <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> which once belonged to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>. Under the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> debt plan, commercial banks would be asked to forgive voluntarily a portion of the loans they have made to poor nations. In return, the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> would provide assurances that the remaining debt would be repaid. The administration has estimated that over the next three years the plan could wipe out about $ 70 billion of the $ 340 billion in debt owed by 39 of the most heavily indebted countries. The <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> would be expected to contribute together between $ 20 billion and $ 25 billion to back the debt reduction effort with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> looking to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other countries running large trade surpluses to assist in the effort by making new loans. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have indicated that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> likely would be among the first beneficiaries of any debt relief strategy. But the debtor nations are already complaining that the plan does not go far enough to provide relief. Some experts have said that any attack on the problem will have to write off 50 percent or more of the debt. Large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks, who hold 30 percent of the outstanding Third World loans, have reacted cautiously to the proposals, fearing that they could cause a stampede by debtor nations demanding debt forgiveness. Already, officials of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> have indicated that they will ask their bank creditors in upcoming negotiations to either provide new loans or slash the value of outstanding loans or the interest rates being paid by half. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, which owes $ 107 billion, is the Third World's second largest debtor, behind the $ 110 billion owed by <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan represents a major departure from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration approach, which emphasized new lending and opposed any broad-based proposals for debt forgiveness. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> approach was crafted by then-Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, who is secretary of state in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, said in a speech last week that the new policy of debt forgiveness would be negotiated on a country-by-country basis with the relief going to those debtor nations willing to adopt necessary economic reforms. At the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> meetings on Sunday, debtor nations issued a statement attacking the Baker approach to Third World debt while welcoming the new approach outlined by <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemboumba-Lepandou </PERSON>, finance minister of <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION> and chairman of the committee representing developing countries, said the <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> plan was `` an important initiative and we are convinced that it will bear fruit.'' However, the <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION> finance minister sidestepped questions about whether the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal went far enough to reduce the debt burden, saying the specifics of the proposal still needed to be worked out in upcoming meetings.
