<HEAD>A Year After Gallaudet Protests, Elisabeth Zinser is Heading For
Idaho</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to CORRECT spelling of Elisabeth, sted Elizabeth,
Zinser.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gallaudet-A Year Later</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Elisabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON>, who was forced to resign last year as the incoming president of the nation's only university for the deaf, looks back on the incident without bitterness and says she's ready for a new challenge as president of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm a pioneering person,'' she said. `` I feel I have to be part of something that is poised for development.'' In March 1988, Ms. <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON> became the focus of a national controversy when she was selected over two deaf finalists to become president of <ORGANIZATION> Gallaudet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> For the previous five years, Ms. <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON> had been vice chancellor for academic affairs at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>. She stayed at that post when the protest over the <LOCATION> Gallaudet </LOCATION> job led her to withdraw before she took office. But now she's going to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, where she'll start July 1 as the first woman president of the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s 9,500-student flagship state university. She said she hopes to strengthen that school's research efforts and its ties with the business community, and will work with <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s Indian and Hispanic communities. And in an interview last week, she wondered aloud if her interest in public service was enhanced by her experience with the deaf students. `` I've got an intense desire to make my life count for something,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Zinser </PERSON>, 49. `` That's why I ca n't just work for any institution.'' Her selection at <LOCATION